  "prompt": "How many milliliters of liguid b-6 vitamins are in 85 milligrams of b-6 vitamin?",
  "response": "To convert milligrams (mg) of vitamin B-6 to milliliters (mL) of liquid vitamin B-6, you need to know the concentration of the liquid solution. The concentration is typically given in mg per mL on the product label.\n\nLet's assume the concentration of the liquid vitamin B-6 is **X mg/mL**.\n\nThe formula to calculate the volume in milliliters is:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Volume (mL)} = \\frac{\\text{Amount of vitamin B-6 (mg)}}{\\text{Concentration (mg/mL)}}\n\\]\n\nIf the concentration is, for example, **25 mg/mL**, then:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Volume (mL)} = \\frac{85 \\, \\text{mg}}{25 \\, \\text{mg/mL}} = 3.4 \\, \\text{mL}\n\\]\n\nIf the concentration is different, substitute the actual concentration value into the formula.\n\n**Key Points:**\n1. Check the concentration of the liquid vitamin B-6 (usually on the product label).\n2. Use the formula above to calculate the volume in milliliters.\n\nIf you provide the concentration, I can give you the exact volume.",
